// Why does this not produce a compiler error?
System.out.println(strictEquals(&quot;abc&quot;, 5));  
```

When the type parameter `T` of `strictEquals` gets inferred by the compiler it tries to find a type that makes the types check out. The result is that it infers a common super-type of `Integer` and `String`, which turns out to be `Object`. (It might also be `Comparable` or `Serializable` or something like that.)

Since both arguments are subtypes to `Object` the method type-checks fine.

One way to make the compiler detect a type error is to provide an explicit type argument to `strictEquals`:

```
// Error: not applicable for the arguments (String, Integer)
System.out.println(Main.&lt;String&gt;strictEquals(&quot;abc&quot;, 5));
```

------

You can force the user to provide a type by adding a class object parameter:

```
System.out.println(Main.strictEquals(String.class, &quot;abc&quot;, 5));

public static &lt;T&gt; boolean strictEquals(Class&lt;T&gt; compareAsType, T a, T b) {
    Objects.requireNonNull(compareAsType);
    return Objects.equals(a, b);
}
```

------

Another work-around might be rely on the fact that types are invariant in their type arguments. For example, only compare boxes of values, like this:

```
Box&lt;String&gt; b1 = new Box&lt;&gt;(&quot;abc&quot;);
Box&lt;Integer&gt; b2 = new Box&lt;&gt;(5);
// Error: not applicable for the arguments (Box&lt;String&gt;, Box&lt;Integer&gt;)
System.out.println(Main.strictEqualsBoxed(b1, b2));

public static &lt;T&gt; boolean strictEqualsBoxed(Box&lt;T&gt; a, Box&lt;T&gt; b) {
    return Objects.equals(a, b);
}

class Box&lt;T&gt; {
    T value;
    public Box(T value) {
        this.value = value;
    }
}
```

But it&#39;s still easy to circumvent:

```
// No error
System.out.println(Main.strictEqualsBoxed(new Box&lt;&gt;(&quot;abc&quot;), new Box&lt;&gt;(5)));
```

Maybe their is some other kind of arcane genetics wizardry to make a better solution...? I don&#39;t think so, but I will now embark on a quest to find out! :)

Java will resolve `T` to the most generic base type that both parameters inherit from, in this case `Object`.

I don&#39;t believe there is any way to use generics for the problem you&#39;re trying to solve. Generics are [erased at runtime](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/339699/java-generics-type-erasure-when-and-what-happens). Note that it&#39;s very common for overridden implementations of `equals` to check (at runtime, not compile-time) that the two compared values have the same type.

Your best alternative would be to create many implementations of `strictEquals` that take in parameters of the same primitive type, for example:
```java
public static boolean strictEquals(int a, int b) {
    return a == b;
}

public static boolean strictEquals(String a, String b) {
    return Objects.equals(a, b);
}
```

