You could remove all other chars then use `startsWith()`:

```
private static void checkString(String str) {
    if (str.replaceAll(&quot;[^\\[.]&quot;, &quot;&quot;).startsWith(&quot;.&quot;)) {
        System.out.println(&quot;period comes first&quot;);
    } else {
        System.out.println(&quot;bracket comes first&quot;);
    }
}
```

The regex `[^\\[.]` means &quot;any character not a `[` or a `.`&quot;, so replacing those with a blank `&quot;&quot;` &quot;deletes&quot; them. This is very slightly &quot;expensive&quot;, but unless your string is huge, we&#39;re talking microseconds.

You are checking for each character more times than you need to; just check once using [`indexOf`][1] and use the fact that it returns `-1` if the character is not found to control your logic. Updating your code:
```java
private static void checkString(String str) {
    int indBr = str.indexOf(&quot;[&quot;);
    int indPrd = str.indexOf(&quot;.&quot;);
 
    if(indPrd &gt;= 0 &amp;&amp; indBr &gt;= 0) {
        if(indPrd &lt; indBr)
            System.out.println(&quot;period comes first&quot;);
        else
            System.out.println(&quot;bracket comes first&quot;);
    }
    else {
    	System.out.println(&quot;No bracket or period&quot;);
    }
}
```
